**Update**  
Mostly I have tried to imagine how your component structure might look like.

The main point is that you want your DropdownTextComponent to render only if its value or its change event handler change.  
For this to occurr, you should avoid rendering it explicitly each time you render the DropdownComponent, as you were doing, but let React handle the rerender for you.  


When you do something like this `props={ &lt;DropdownTextComponent /&gt; }`, the expression inside the brackets is evaluated right away, at each render of the component. Moreover you are not passing anything to the child component.  
But if you do something like this `&lt;DropdownComponent&gt;&lt;DropdownTextComponent value={value} onChange={onChange} /&gt;&lt;/DropdownComponent&gt;` React will parse the whole structure of your App and render each node only if its props or state have changed.   


For this to work, since the parent here is a custom component, you will have to explicitly add its children in its render method. You can do this by using the special React prop `children` that contains everything you have defined as a descendant of your component.

