I see that you&#39;re animating text. There are many ways to do this, but in this case I think that using milliseconds to time your animation would do it justice. It could have been the other way around, but with plain text I think the easier for you will be the better.

For a more complicated purpose, I would suggest you to [learn about a design pattern named &quot;States&quot;](https://sourcemaking.com/design_patterns/state). Yet, for this animation, we&#39;ll ninja our way through it in a way which will be close to what you already did, yet better for your purpose.

We&#39;ll use a simple `switch`, with a state-like logic.

A switch is a simple statement which compare a variable to a succession of possible values. As soon as it reaches a value it recognize, it &quot;enters&quot; this case and do whatever is written there.

You can imagine it as a more rudimentary `If ... Else If ... Else` statement. It&#39;s not exactly the same, as than one `case` inside the switch can be read as you have to &quot;break&quot; a case to avoid the other ones being run too, but in the end it&#39;s quite similar, yet often easier to read.

We&#39;ll use the `switch` because it&#39;s easy to use, and because it&#39;ll be clean for you to read and understand.

A &quot;state&quot; is a way of defining what is currently happening with a specific object (which is your whole animation in the case).

We&#39;ll need a new variable to hold the current state. We&#39;ll call it &quot;state&quot; I guess. It&#39;ll be a string. It could be anything, I guess, but a String will be easy to read for you, and as a wise man once said: code for humans, and as a side-effect computers will be able to read it.

The switch will check what the current state is, and acts accordingly. This way, you&#39;ll be able to reset your timer every time you change to a new state. I&#39;m modify your current code to reflect this, and let you do most of the job.

Also, one last thing: to make things easier, I&#39;m giving you this class: Delay. It&#39;s something I coded as a student, and I still use it from time to time. It acts as a timer. This class will permit you to set an amount of time and check if it&#39;s expired.

    class Delay {
      protected int limit;
    
      public Delay() {limit = millis();}
      public Delay (int l) {
        limit = millis() + l;
      }
    
      public boolean expired () {
        if (millis() &gt; limit) { return true; }
    
        return false;
      }
    }

